    "details": {
      "biography": {
        "value": "<p><em>A well-dressed human man in his late thirties with a neatly styled moustache, expressive eyes, and a finely tailored coat with gold embroidery and distant-market-inspired patterns. He wears a distinctive saffron-colored ring that he claims was gifted by a foreign prince.</em></p><h3>Personality</h3><p>Warm, theatrical, flattering, and endlessly talkative. Leoric sells stories as much as spices, and every conversation becomes a performance. He is charming, clever, and careful to sound more worldly than he truly is.</p><h3>Motivation</h3><p>To maintain his reputation as a worldly importer, grow his wealth, and keep anyone from discovering that most of his exotic travel stories are fabricated.</p><h3>Mannerisms</h3><p>Twists his pointed moustache while bargaining; waves scented spice samples under a customer's nose; lowers his voice dramatically before invented travel stories; taps his saffron ring when nervous.</p><h3>Voice &amp; Accent</h3><p>Smooth, warm, and theatrical. He speaks with polished confidence and sprinkles his stories with invented foreign phrases.</p><h3>Bonds, Ideals, Flaws</h3><ul><li><strong>Bond:</strong> Attached to Bramwell's Aromas, the small fortune he has built, and the public image that keeps his customers enchanted.</li><li><strong>Ideal:</strong> Presentation is half the truth. People do not only buy goods; they buy the feeling of owning something rare.</li><li><strong>Flaw:</strong> He exaggerates constantly and lies reflexively when his status is questioned. His pride makes it hard for him to admit ignorance.</li></ul><hr><h3>GM Notes</h3><p>Use Leoric as a comic but useful merchant NPC. Not evil, but vain and dishonest about his background. Can provide rare spices, rumors from wealthy households, gossip from merchants, and occasional access to private culinary events.</p><h3>Secrets</h3><p>Leoric has never visited the distant lands he describes. His famous saffron ring is not a royal gift but a clever forgery. One recent shipment may contain an alchemical ingredient tied to smugglers.</p><h3>Relationships</h3><p>Wealthy citizens: loyal customers who enjoy his stories. Restaurant owners: regular buyers of his spice blends. Real foreign traders: useful suppliers who know he has never traveled as far as he claims. Joran Hollowquill: could expose gaps in Leoric's fabricated historical anecdotes.</p><h3>Plot Hooks</h3><p>1. A customer asks the party to verify whether Leoric's rare spice shipment is genuine.\n2. A real foreign trader arrives and publicly challenges Leoric's invented travel stories.\n3. Someone steals Leoric's ledger, exposing wealthy customers and suspicious private orders.\n4. A spice blend accidentally contains a rare alchemical ingredient wanted by smugglers.\n5. Leoric hires the party to protect his reputation during a market festival.</p><h3>Encounter Ideas</h3><p>1. Social bargaining scene inside Bramwell's Aromas.\n2. Market festival where Leoric performs an exaggerated spice demonstration.\n3. Investigation into counterfeit delicacies and forged import seals.\n4. A rival merchant tries to expose Leoric in front of noble customers.</p>",
